# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fixed-timestep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] In network programming, due to the unpredictable nature of internet connections, delta timing is used in a similar way to variably update the movement information received via the computer network, regardless of how long it took to receive the next data packet of movement information.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] It is often done by calling a timer every frame per second that holds the time between now and last call.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Thereafter the resulting number (delta time) is used to calculate how far, for instance, a video game character would have travelled during that time.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] This results in the character taking the same amount of real world time to move across the screen regardless of the rate of update, and whether the delay is caused by lack of processing power or a slow internet connection.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] In network programming, this keeps the game world of each computer in sync with the others, by making sure each client eventually sees the same activity at the same time, even if more time has passed since the last update for some clients than others.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Big enough delays will eventually negatively affect the gameplay experience, but using Delta Time keeps the gameplay consistent so long as the computer and internet connection meet the minimum hardware requirements of the game.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Delta time can be used to measure how long a given program took to execute in real-time.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] The python snippet below shows how an example function's execution time can be calculated using the delta of times before and after execution.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Delta-time and frame rate are not always related.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Video games fall into one of two categories regarding frame rate: frame rate dependent or frame rate independent.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Frame rate Dependent games have a frame rate that varies based on the computer running the software.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] For example, if a frame rate dependent game runs at 300 frames per second (fps) on a computer with a refresh rate of 120 hertz (Hz), then it would run at 150 fps on a computer with a refresh rate of 60 Hz.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] A standard delta-time expression can create pause screens and intentional slow-motion effects in frame rate-dependent games.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Standard delta-time formulas are seldom used for standard game-play because the delta-time between frames varies greatly depending on the refresh rate of the computer on which it is running.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] If a game is frame rate independent, the frame rate is preset and runs identically across all computers regardless of their specifications.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Frame rate independence limits the maximum graphics quality to make the game available to more consumers.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Frame rate independence is particularly popular in mobile games and games optimized for lower-end computers such as Chromebooks.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] In frame rate independent games, the delta-time between frames is consistent across the entire game.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] This standardization means that one delta-time expression can create a consistent frame rate for all users on all types of computers.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Delta-timing can excel anytime a game's frame rate needs to be independent of its hardware.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] One example of this could be games that need to run on mobile devices or low-end computers.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] In some cases, video game developers use delta-timing to standardize the movement speed of an object on the screen.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] For example, if a character moves across the screen at a constant rate, delta-timing can ensure that this movement speed is consistent and does not fluctuate.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] Using delta-timing for movement is particularly useful for users who possess inconsistent internet or low-end computer hardware.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] This method can also regulate the movement of on-screen objects.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] One disadvantage of using delta-timing for movement is that it can be complicated for games that incorporate a wide variety of movements and movement speeds.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] For example, a game could have a specified walking speed and sprinting speed for all characters; however, characters may also drive cars, boats, planes, and other vehicles.
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] If the developer wants each of these movement speeds to be different (to make the game as realistic as possible), they would need a separate delta-time expression for each movement speed (that is only assuming these movements occur at a constant rate).
[src:fixed-timestep/delta-time] If the movements do not occur at a constant rate, delta-timing expressions are rendered ineffective.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In mathematics and computational science, the **Euler method** (also called the **forward Euler method**) is a first-order numerical procedure for solving ordinary differential equations (ODEs) with a given initial value.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] It is the most basic explicit method for numerical integration of ordinary differential equations and is the simplest Runge–Kutta method.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Euler method is named after Leonhard Euler, who first proposed it in his book *Institutionum calculi integralis* (published 1768–1770).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Euler method is a first-order method, which means that the local error (error per step) is proportional to the square of the step size, and the global error (error at a given time) is proportional to the step size.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Euler method often serves as the basis to construct more complex methods, e.g., predictor–corrector method.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Consider the problem of calculating the shape of an unknown curve which starts at a given point and satisfies a given differential equation.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Here, a differential equation can be thought of as a formula by which the slope of the tangent line to the curve can be computed at any point on the curve, once the position of that point has been calculated.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The idea is that while the curve is initially unknown, its starting point, which we denote by $A_{0},$ is known (see Figure 1).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Then, from the differential equation, the slope to the curve at $A_{0}$ can be computed, and so, the tangent line.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Take a small step along that tangent line up to a point $A_{1}.$ Along this small step, the slope does not change too much, so $A_{1}$ will be close to the curve.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] If we pretend that $A_{1}$ is still on the curve, the same reasoning as for the point $A_{0}$ above can be used.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In general, this curve does not diverge too far from the original unknown curve, and the error between the two curves can be made small if the step size is small enough and the interval of computation is finite.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] When given the values for $t_{0}$ and $y(t_{0})$ , and the derivative of y is a given function of t and y denoted as $y'(t)=f\left(t,y(t)\right)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Next, choose a value h for the size of every step along t-axis, and set $t_{n}=t_{0}+nh$ (or equivalently $t_{n+1}=t_{n}+h$ ).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The value of $y_{n}$ is an approximation of the solution at time $t_{n}$ , i.e., $y_{n}\approx y(t_{n})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Euler method is explicit, i.e. the solution $y_{n+1}$ is an explicit function of $y_{i}$ for $i\leq n$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] While the Euler method integrates a first-order ODE, any ODE of order N can be represented as a system of first-order ODEs.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] These first-order systems can be handled by Euler's method or, in fact, by any other scheme for first-order systems.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] we would like to use the Euler method to approximate $y(4)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In this simple differential equation, the function f is defined by $f(t,y)=y$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] By doing the above step, we have found the slope of the line that is tangent to the solution curve at the point $(0,1)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Recall that the slope is defined as the change in y divided by the change in t , or ${\textstyle {\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta t}}}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Since the step size is the change in t , when we multiply the step size and the slope of the tangent, we get a change in y value.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This value is then added to the initial y value to obtain the next value to be used for computations.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The above steps should be repeated to find $y_{2}$ , $y_{3}$ and $y_{4}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Due to the repetitive nature of this algorithm, it can be helpful to organize computations in a chart form, as seen below, to avoid making errors.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The conclusion of this computation is that $y_{4}=16$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The exact solution of the differential equation is $y(t)=e^{t}$ , so $y(4)=e^{4}\approx 54.598$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Although the approximation of the Euler method was not very precise in this specific case, particularly due to a large value step size h , its behaviour is qualitatively correct as the figure shows.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] As suggested in the introduction, the Euler method is more accurate if the step size h is smaller.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The table below shows the result with different step sizes.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The top row corresponds to the example in the previous section, and the second row is illustrated in the figure.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The error recorded in the last column of the table is the difference between the exact solution at $t=4$ and the Euler approximation.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In the bottom of the table, the step size is half the step size in the previous row, and the error is also approximately half the error in the previous row.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This suggests that the error is roughly proportional to the step size, at least for fairly small values of the step size.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This is true in general, also for other equations; see the section *Global truncation error* for more details.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Other methods, such as the midpoint method also illustrated in the figures, behave more favourably: the global error of the midpoint method is roughly proportional to the *square* of the step size.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] For this reason, the Euler method is said to be a first-order method, while the midpoint method is second order.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] We can extrapolate from the above table that the step size needed to get an answer that is correct to three decimal places is approximately 0.00001, meaning that we need 400,000 steps.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This large number of steps entails a high computational cost.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] For this reason, higher-order methods are employed such as Runge–Kutta methods or linear multistep methods, especially if a high accuracy is desired.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Euler method can be derived in a number of ways.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] If this is substituted in the Taylor expansion and the quadratic and higher-order terms are ignored, the Euler method arises.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Taylor expansion is used below to analyze the error committed by the Euler method, and it can be extended to produce Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] A closely related derivation is to substitute the forward finite difference formula for the derivative, $y'(t_{0})\approx {\frac {y(t_{0}+h)-y(t_{0})}{h}}$ in the differential equation $y'=f(t,y)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] A similar computation leads to the midpoint method and the backward Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This line of thought can be continued to arrive at various linear multistep methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The local truncation error of the Euler method is the error made in a single step.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] It is the difference between the numerical solution after one step, $y_{1}$ , and the exact solution at time $t_{1}=t_{0}+h$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This result is valid if y has a bounded third derivative.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This shows that for small h , the local truncation error is approximately proportional to $h^{2}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This makes the Euler method less accurate than higher-order techniques such as Runge–Kutta methods and linear multistep methods, for which the local truncation error is proportional to a higher power of the step size.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] A slightly different formulation for the local truncation error can be obtained by using the Lagrange form for the remainder term in Taylor's theorem.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In the above expressions for the error, the second derivative of the unknown exact solution y can be replaced by an expression involving the right-hand side of the differential equation.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The global truncation error is the error at a fixed time $t_{i}$ , after however many steps the method needs to take to reach that time from the initial time.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The global truncation error is the cumulative effect of the local truncation errors committed in each step.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The number of steps is easily determined to be ${\textstyle {\frac {t_{i}-t_{0}}{h}}}$ , which is proportional to ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{h}}}$ , and the error committed in each step is proportional to $h^{2}$ (see the previous section).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Thus, it is to be expected that the global truncation error will be proportional to h .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This intuitive reasoning can be made precise.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] where M is an upper bound on the second derivative of y on the given interval and L is the Lipschitz constant of f .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Or more simply, when $y'(t)=f(t,y)$ , the value ${\textstyle L={\text{max}}\left(|{\frac {d}{dy}}\left[f(t,y)\right]|\right)}$ (such that t is treated as a constant).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In contrast, ${\textstyle M=\max \left(\left|{\frac {d^{2}}{dt^{2}}}\left[y(t)\right]\right|\right)}$ where function $y(t)$ is the exact solution which only contains the t variable.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The precise form of this bound is of little practical importance, as in most cases the bound vastly overestimates the actual error committed by the Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] What is important is that it shows that the global truncation error is (approximately) proportional to h .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] For this reason, the Euler method is said to be first order.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The Euler method can also be numerically unstable, especially for stiff equations, meaning that the numerical solution grows very large for equations where the exact solution does not.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This can be illustrated using the linear equation $y'=-2.3y,\qquad y(0)=1.$ The exact solution is $y(t)=e^{-2.3t}$ , which decays to zero as $t\to \infty$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] However, if the Euler method is applied to this equation with step size $h=1$ , then the numerical solution is qualitatively wrong: It oscillates and grows (see the figure).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] If a smaller step size is used, for instance $h=0.7$ , then the numerical solution does decay to zero.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] If the Euler method is applied to the linear equation $y'=ky$ , then the numerical solution is unstable if the product $hk$ is outside the region $\left\{z\in \mathbf {C} \,{\big |}\,|z+1|\leq 1\right\},$ illustrated on the right.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This region is called the (linear) *stability region*.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In the example, $k=-2.3$ , so if $h=1$ then $hk=-2.3$ which is outside the stability region, and thus the numerical solution is unstable.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This limitation — along with its slow convergence of error with h — means that the Euler method is not often used, except as a simple example of numerical integration.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Frequently models of physical systems contain terms representing fast-decaying elements (i.e. with large negative exponential arguments).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Even when these are not of interest in the overall solution, the instability they can induce means that an exceptionally small timestep would be required if the Euler method is used.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In step n of the Euler method, the rounding error is roughly of the magnitude $\varepsilon y_{n}$ where $\varepsilon$ is the machine epsilon.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Assuming that the rounding errors are independent random variables, the expected total rounding error is proportional to ${\textstyle {\frac {\varepsilon }{\sqrt {h}}}}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Thus, for extremely small values of the step size the truncation error will be small but the effect of rounding error may be big.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Most of the effect of rounding error can be easily avoided if compensated summation is used in the formula for the Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The backward Euler method is an implicit method, meaning that the formula for the backward Euler method has $y_{n+1}$ on both sides, so when applying the backward Euler method we have to solve an equation.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This makes the implementation more costly.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] Other modifications of the Euler method that help with stability yield the exponential Euler method or the semi-implicit Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] More complicated methods can achieve a higher order (and more accuracy).
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] One possibility is to use more function evaluations.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] This is illustrated by the midpoint method which is already mentioned in this article: $y_{n+1}=y_{n}+hf\left(t_{n}+{\tfrac {1}{2}}h,y_{n}+{\tfrac {1}{2}}hf(t_{n},y_{n})\right).$ This leads to the family of Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] The other possibility is to use more past values, as illustrated by the two-step Adams–Bashforth method: $y_{n+1}=y_{n}+{\tfrac {3}{2}}hf(t_{n},y_{n})-{\tfrac {1}{2}}hf(t_{n-1},y_{n-1}).$ This leads to the family of linear multistep methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/euler-method] In the film *Hidden Figures*, Katherine Johnson resorts to the Euler method in calculating the re-entry of astronaut John Glenn from Earth orbit.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] In the mathematical subfield of numerical analysis, **numerical stability** is a generally desirable property of numerical algorithms.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The precise definition of stability depends on the context: one important context is numerical linear algebra, and another is algorithms for solving ordinary and partial differential equations by discrete approximation.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] In numerical linear algebra, the principal concern is instabilities caused by proximity to singularities of various kinds, such as very small or nearly colliding eigenvalues.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] On the other hand, in numerical algorithms for differential equations the concern is the growth of round-off errors and/or small fluctuations in initial data which might cause a large deviation of final answer from the exact solution.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Some numerical algorithms may damp out the small fluctuations (errors) in the input data; others might magnify such errors.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Calculations that can be proven not to magnify approximation errors are called *numerically stable*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] One of the common tasks of numerical analysis is to try to select algorithms which are *robust* – that is to say, do not produce a wildly different result for a very small change in the input data.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] An opposite phenomenon is **instability**.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Typically, an algorithm involves an approximative method, and in some cases one could prove that the algorithm would approach the right solution in some limit (when using actual real numbers, not floating point numbers).
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Even in this case, there is no guarantee that it would converge to the correct solution, because the floating-point round-off or truncation errors can be magnified, instead of damped, causing the deviation from the exact solution to grow exponentially.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] There are different ways to formalize the concept of stability.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The following definitions of forward, backward, and mixed stability are often used in numerical linear algebra.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Consider the problem to be solved by the numerical algorithm as a function f mapping the data x to the solution y.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The result of the algorithm, say y*, will usually deviate from the "true" solution y.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The main causes of error are round-off error and truncation error.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The *forward error* of the algorithm is the difference between the result and the "true" solution; in this case, Δ*y* = *y** − *y*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The *backward error* is the smallest Δ*x* such that *f* (*x* + Δ*x*) = *y**; in other words, the backward error tells us what problem the algorithm actually solved.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The forward and backward error are related by the condition number: the forward error is at most as big in magnitude as the condition number multiplied by the magnitude of the backward error.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] In many cases, it is more natural to consider the relative error ${\frac {|\Delta x|}{|x|}}$ instead of the absolute error Δ*x*.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The algorithm is said to be *backward stable* if the backward error is small for all inputs x.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Of course, "small" is a relative term and its definition will depend on the context.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Often, we want the error to be of the same order as, or perhaps only a few orders of magnitude bigger than, the unit round-off.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The usual definition of numerical stability uses a more general concept, called *mixed stability*, which combines the forward error and the backward error.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] An algorithm is stable in this sense if it solves a nearby problem approximately, i.e., if there exists a Δ*x* such that both Δ*x* is small and *f* (*x* + Δ*x*) − *y** is small.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Hence, a backward stable algorithm is always stable.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] An algorithm is *forward stable* if its forward error divided by the condition number of the problem is small.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] This means that an algorithm is forward stable if it has a forward error of magnitude similar to some backward stable algorithm.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The above definitions are particularly relevant in situations where truncation errors are not important.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] In other contexts, for instance when solving differential equations, a different definition of numerical stability is used.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] In numerical ordinary differential equations, various concepts of numerical stability exist, for instance A-stability.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] They are related to some concept of stability in the dynamical systems sense, often Lyapunov stability.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] It is important to use a stable method when solving a stiff equation.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Yet another definition is used in numerical partial differential equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] An algorithm for solving a linear evolutionary partial differential equation is stable if the total variation of the numerical solution at a fixed time remains bounded as the step size goes to zero.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The Lax equivalence theorem states that an algorithm converges if it is consistent and stable (in this sense).
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Stability is sometimes achieved by including numerical diffusion.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Numerical diffusion is a mathematical term which ensures that roundoff and other errors in the calculation get spread out and do not add up to cause the calculation to "blow up".
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Von Neumann stability analysis is a commonly used procedure for the stability analysis of finite difference schemes as applied to linear partial differential equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] These results do not hold for nonlinear PDEs, where a general, consistent definition of stability is complicated by many properties absent in linear equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Computing the square root of 2 (which is roughly 1.41421) is a well-posed problem.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Many algorithms solve this problem by starting with an initial approximation *x*0 to ${\sqrt {2}}$ , for instance *x*0 = 1.4, and then computing improved guesses *x*1, *x*2, etc.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] One such method is the famous Babylonian method, which is given by *x**k*+1 = (*xk*+ 2/*xk*)/2.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] A few iterations of each scheme are calculated in table form below, with initial guesses *x*0 = 1.4 and *x*0 = 1.42.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Observe that the Babylonian method converges quickly regardless of the initial guess, whereas Method X converges extremely slowly with initial guess *x*0 = 1.4 and diverges for initial guess *x*0 = 1.42.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Hence, the Babylonian method is numerically stable, while Method X is numerically unstable.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] Numerical stability is affected by the number of the significant digits the machine keeps.
[src:fixed-timestep/numerical-stability] The desired value, computed using infinite precision, is 11.174755...
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In numerical analysis, the **Runge–Kutta methods** (English: /ˈrʊŋəˈkʊtɑː/ ⓘ *RUUNG-ə-KUUT-tah*) are a family of implicit and explicit iterative methods, which include the Euler method, used in temporal discretization for the approximate solutions of simultaneous nonlinear equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] These methods were developed around 1900 by the German mathematicians Carl Runge and Wilhelm Kutta.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The most widely known member of the Runge–Kutta family is generally referred to as "RK4", the "classic Runge–Kutta method" or simply as "the Runge–Kutta method".
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Here y is an unknown function (scalar or vector) of time t , which we would like to approximate; we are told that ${\frac {dy}{dt}}$ , the rate at which y changes, is a function of t and of y itself.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] At the initial time $t_{0}$ the corresponding y value is $y_{0}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The function f and the initial conditions $t_{0}$ , $y_{0}$ are given.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In averaging the four slopes, greater weight is given to the slopes at the midpoint.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] If f is independent of y , so that the differential equation is equivalent to a simple integral, then RK4 is Simpson's rule.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The RK4 method is a fourth-order method, meaning that the local truncation error is on the order of $O(h^{5})$ , while the total accumulated error is on the order of $O(h^{4})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In many practical applications the function f is independent of t (so called autonomous system, or time-invariant system, especially in physics), and their increments are not computed at all and not passed to function f , with only the final formula for $t_{n+1}$ used.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The family of explicit Runge–Kutta methods is a generalization of the RK4 method mentioned above.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Note: the above equations may have different but equivalent definitions in some texts.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] To specify a particular method, one needs to provide the integer *s* (the number of stages), and the coefficients *aij* (for 1 ≤ *j* < *i* ≤ *s*), *bi* (for *i* = 1, 2, ..., *s*) and *ci* (for *i* = 2, 3, ..., *s*).
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The matrix [*aij*] is called the *Runge–Kutta matrix*, while the *bi* and *ci* are known as the *weights* and the *nodes*.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] These data are usually arranged in a mnemonic device, known as a *Butcher tableau* (after John C.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] There are also accompanying requirements if one requires the method to have a certain order *p*, meaning that the local truncation error is O(*hp*+1).
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] These can be derived from the definition of the truncation error itself.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This condition alone, however, is neither sufficient, nor necessary for consistency.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In general, if an explicit s -stage Runge–Kutta method has order p , then it can be proven that the number of stages must satisfy $s\geq p$ and if $p\geq 5$ , then $s\geq p+1$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] However, it is not known whether these bounds are *sharp* in all cases.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In some cases, it is proven that the bound cannot be achieved.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] For instance, Butcher proved that for $p>6$ , there is no explicit method with $s=p+1$ stages.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Butcher also proved that for $p>7$ , there is no explicit Runge-Kutta method with $p+2$ stages.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In general, however, it remains an open problem what the precise minimum number of stages s is for an explicit Runge–Kutta method to have order p .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The provable bound above then implies that we cannot find methods of orders $p=1,2,\ldots ,6$ that require fewer stages than the methods we already know for these orders.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The work of Butcher also proves that 7th and 8th order methods have a minimum of 9 and 11 stages, respectively.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] An example of an explicit method of order 6 with 7 stages can be found in Ref.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Explicit methods of order 7 with 9 stages and explicit methods of order 8 with 11 stages are also known.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A slight variation of "the" Runge–Kutta method is also due to Kutta in 1901 and is called the 3/8-rule.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The primary advantage this method has is that almost all of the error coefficients are smaller than in the popular method, but it requires slightly more floating-point operations per time step.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] However, the simplest Runge–Kutta method is the (forward) Euler method, given by the formula $y_{n+1}=y_{n}+hf(t_{n},y_{n})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This is the only consistent explicit Runge–Kutta method with one stage.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In this family, $\alpha ={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ gives the midpoint method, $\alpha =1$ is Heun's method, and $\alpha ={\tfrac {2}{3}}$ is Ralston's method.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] As an example, consider the two-stage second-order Runge–Kutta method with α = 2/3, also known as Ralston method.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] with step size *h* = 0.025, so the method needs to take four steps.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The numerical solutions correspond to the underlined values.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Explicit Runge–Kutta methods are generally unsuitable for the solution of stiff equations because their region of absolute stability is small; in particular, it is bounded.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This issue is especially important in the solution of partial differential equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The instability of explicit Runge–Kutta methods motivates the development of implicit methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The difference with an explicit method is that in an explicit method, the sum over *j* only goes up to *i* − 1.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This also shows up in the Butcher tableau: the coefficient matrix $a_{ij}$ of an explicit method is lower triangular.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The consequence of this difference is that at every step, a system of algebraic equations has to be solved.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This increases the computational cost considerably.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] If a method with *s* stages is used to solve a differential equation with *m* components, then the system of algebraic equations has *ms* components.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] which can be re-arranged to get the formula for the backward Euler method listed above.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Another example for an implicit Runge–Kutta method is the trapezoidal rule.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The trapezoidal rule is a collocation method (as discussed in that article).
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] All collocation methods are implicit Runge–Kutta methods, but not all implicit Runge–Kutta methods are collocation methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The Gauss–Legendre methods form a family of collocation methods based on Gauss quadrature.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A Gauss–Legendre method with *s* stages has order 2*s* (thus, methods with arbitrarily high order can be constructed).
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The advantage of implicit Runge–Kutta methods over explicit ones is their greater stability, especially when applied to stiff equations.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Consider the linear test equation $y'=\lambda y$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] where *e* stands for the vector of ones.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The function *r* is called the *stability function*.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] It follows from the formula that *r* is the quotient of two polynomials of degree *s* if the method has *s* stages.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Explicit methods have a strictly lower triangular matrix *A*, which implies that det(*I* − *zA*) = 1 and that the stability function is a polynomial.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The numerical solution to the linear test equation decays to zero if | *r*(*z*) | < 1 with *z* = *h*λ.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The set of such *z* is called the *domain of absolute stability*.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In particular, the method is said to be absolute stable if all *z* with Re(*z*) < 0 are in the domain of absolute stability.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The stability function of an explicit Runge–Kutta method is a polynomial, so explicit Runge–Kutta methods can never be A-stable.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] If the method has order *p*, then the stability function satisfies $r(z)={\textrm {e}}^{z}+O(z^{p+1})$ as $z\to 0$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Thus, it is of interest to study quotients of polynomials of given degrees that approximate the exponential function the best.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A Padé approximant with numerator of degree *m* and denominator of degree *n* is A-stable if and only if *m* ≤ *n* ≤ *m* + 2.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The Gauss–Legendre method with *s* stages has order 2*s*, so its stability function is the Padé approximant with *m* = *n* = *s*.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This shows that A-stable Runge–Kutta can have arbitrarily high order.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] In contrast, the order of A-stable linear multistep methods cannot exceed two.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Adaptive methods are designed to produce an estimate of the local truncation error of a single Runge–Kutta step.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This is done by having two methods, one with order p and one with order $p-1$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] These methods are interwoven, i.e., they have common intermediate steps.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Thanks to this, estimating the error has little or negligible computational cost compared to a step with the higher-order method.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] During the integration, the step size is adapted such that the estimated error stays below a user-defined threshold: If the error is too high, a step is repeated with a lower step size; if the error is much smaller, the step size is increased to save time.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This results in an (almost), optimal step size, which saves computation time.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Moreover, the user does not have to spend time on finding an appropriate step size.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] where $k_{i}$ are the same as for the higher-order method.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The Runge–Kutta–Fehlberg method has two methods of orders 5 and 4.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] However, the simplest adaptive Runge–Kutta method involves combining Heun's method, which is order 2, with the Euler method, which is order 1.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Other adaptive Runge–Kutta methods are the Bogacki–Shampine method (orders 3 and 2), the Cash–Karp method and the Dormand–Prince method (both with orders 5 and 4).
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A Runge–Kutta method is said to be *nonconfluent* if all the $c_{i},\,i=1,2,\ldots ,s$ are distinct.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] There are two derivatives two approximates, a Runge-Kutta-Nyström methods hence uses two Runge-Kutta matrices $a_{ij},a'_{ij}$ , and two sets of weights $b_{i},b'_{i}$ , but still only needs one set of nodes $c_{i}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Assume the approximations have been carried out up to $t_{n}$ , with $y_{n}$ the approximation of $y(t_{n})$ and $y'_{n}$ the approximation of ${\frac {dy}{dt}}(t_{n})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Where $g_{i},g'_{i}$ are the intermediate approximations of y and ${\frac {dy}{dt}}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] It is strictly equivalent to work with the values $k_{j}=f(t_{n}+c_{j}h,g'_{j},g_{j})$ where the $g_{j},g'_{j}$ have been replaced with their formula, instead of working with $g_{i},g'_{i}$ , similarly to what we previously did with Runge-Kutta methods, but the system is easier to write this way.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A Runge-Kutta-Nyström method is said to be explicit if both $A,A'$ are strictly lower triangular, and in this case, the sums ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{s}}$ in the expressions of $g_{i},g'_{i}$ , may be replaced with ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{i-1}}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Additionally, a Runge-Kutta-Nyström method is said to be of order p if the local truncation error of both $y_{n+1},y'_{n+1}$ is $O(h^{p+1})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] This special case is particularly interesting since it allows for greater order than what a Runge-Kutta-Nyström can achieve in general.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The *A-stability* concept for the solution of differential equations is related to the linear autonomous equation $y'=\lambda y$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] Dahlquist (1963) proposed the investigation of stability of numerical schemes when applied to nonlinear systems that satisfy a monotonicity condition.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] The corresponding concepts were defined as *G-stability* for multistep methods (and the related one-leg methods) and *B-stability* (Butcher, 1975) for Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A Runge–Kutta method applied to the non-linear system $y'=f(y)$ , which verifies $\langle f(y)-f(z),\ y-z\rangle \leq 0$ , is called *B-stable*, if this condition implies $\|y_{n+1}-z_{n+1}\|\leq \|y_{n}-z_{n}\|$ for two numerical solutions.
[src:fixed-timestep/runge-kutta-methods] A sufficient condition for *B-stability* is: B and Q are non-negative definite.
