[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] This equation, for various choices of the potential function V , can be used to describe the evolution of diverse physical systems, from the motion of interacting molecules to the orbit of the planets.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Typically, an initial position $\mathbf {x} (0)=\mathbf {x} _{0}$ and an initial velocity $\mathbf {v} (0)={\dot {\mathbf {x} }}(0)=\mathbf {v} _{0}$ are also given.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] To discretize and numerically solve this initial value problem, a time step $\Delta t>0$ is chosen, and the sampling-point sequence $t_{n}=n\,\Delta t$ considered.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The task is to construct a sequence of points $\mathbf {x} _{n}$ that closely follow the points $\mathbf {x} (t_{n})$ on the trajectory of the exact solution.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The time symmetry inherent in the method reduces the level of local errors introduced into the integration by the discretization by removing all odd-degree terms, here the terms in $\Delta t$ of degree three.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Caution should be applied to the fact that the acceleration here is computed from the exact solution, $\mathbf {a} (t)=\mathbf {A} {\bigl (}\mathbf {x} (t){\bigr )}$ , whereas in the iteration it is computed at the central iteration point, $\mathbf {a} _{n}=\mathbf {A} (\mathbf {x} _{n})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] In computing the global error, that is the distance between exact solution and approximation sequence, those two terms do not cancel exactly, influencing the order of the global error.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] To gain insight into the relation of local and global errors, it is helpful to examine simple examples where the exact solution, as well as the approximate solution, can be expressed in explicit formulas.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The standard example for this task is the exponential function.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Consider the linear differential equation ${\ddot {x}}(t)=w^{2}x(t)$ with a constant w .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Its exact basis solutions are $e^{wt}$ and $e^{-wt}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Note that at the start of the Verlet iteration at step $n=1$ , time $t=t_{1}=\Delta t$ , computing $\mathbf {x} _{2}$ , one already needs the position vector $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ at time $t=t_{1}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] At first sight, this could give problems, because the initial conditions are known only at the initial time $t_{0}=0$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The error on the first time step then is of order ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{3}\right)}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Moreover, to obtain this second-order global error, the initial error needs to be of at least third order.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] A disadvantage of the Størmer–Verlet method is that if the time step ( $\Delta t$ ) changes, the method does not approximate the solution to the differential equation.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The velocities are not explicitly given in the basic Størmer equation, but often they are necessary for the calculation of certain physical quantities like the kinetic energy.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] This can create technical challenges in molecular dynamics simulations, because kinetic energy and instantaneous temperatures at time t cannot be calculated for a system until the positions are known at time $t+\Delta t$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Note that this velocity term is a step behind the position term, since this is for the velocity at time t , not $t+\Delta t$ , meaning that $\mathbf {v} _{n}={\tfrac {\mathbf {x} _{n+1}-\mathbf {x} _{n-1}}{2\Delta t}}$ is a second-order approximation to $\mathbf {v} (t_{n})$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] A related, and more commonly used algorithm is the velocity Verlet algorithm, similar to the leapfrog method, except that the velocity and position are calculated at the same value of the time variable (leapfrog does not, as the name suggests).
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] It can be shown that the error in the velocity Verlet is of the same order as in the basic Verlet.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Note that the velocity algorithm is not necessarily more memory-consuming, because, in basic Verlet, we keep track of two vectors of position, while in velocity Verlet, we keep track of one vector of position and one vector of velocity.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Derive $\mathbf {a} (t+\Delta t)$ from the interaction potential using $\mathbf {x} (t+\Delta t)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] This algorithm also works with variable time steps, and is identical to the 'kick-drift-kick' form of leapfrog method integration.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Note, however, that this algorithm assumes that acceleration $\mathbf {a} (t+\Delta t)$ only depends on position $\mathbf {x} (t+\Delta t)$ and does not depend on velocity $\mathbf {v} (t+\Delta t)$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] One might note that the long-term results of velocity Verlet, and similarly of leapfrog are one order better than the semi-implicit Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The algorithms are almost identical up to a shift by half a time step in the velocity.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] This can be proven by rotating the above loop to start at step 3 and then noticing that the acceleration term in step 1 could be eliminated by combining steps 2 and 4.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The only difference is that the midpoint velocity in velocity Verlet is considered the final velocity in semi-implicit Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The global error of all Euler methods is of order one, whereas the global error of this method is, similar to the midpoint method, of order two.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The same goes for all other conserved quantities of the system like linear or angular momentum, that are always preserved or nearly preserved in a symplectic integrator.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The velocity Verlet method is a special case of the Newmark-beta method with $\beta =0$ and ${\textstyle \gamma ={\tfrac {1}{2}}}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Since **velocity Verlet** is a generally useful algorithm in 3D applications, a solution written in C++ could look like below.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] This type of position integration will significantly increase accuracy in 3D simulations and games when compared with the regular Euler method.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The global truncation error of the Verlet method is ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{2}\right)}$ , both for position and velocity.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] This is in contrast with the fact that the local error in position is only ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{4}\right)}$ as described above.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The difference is due to the accumulation of the local truncation error over all of the iterations.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Because the velocity is determined in a non-cumulative way from the positions in the Verlet integrator, the global error in velocity is also ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{2}\right)}$ .
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] In molecular dynamics simulations, the global error is typically far more important than the local error, and the Verlet integrator is therefore known as a second-order integrator.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Systems of multiple particles with constraints are simpler to solve with Verlet integration than with Euler methods.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Constraints between points may be, for example, potentials constraining them to a specific distance or attractive forces.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] They may be modeled as springs connecting the particles.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Using springs of infinite stiffness, the model may then be solved with a Verlet algorithm.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Verlet integration is useful because it directly relates the force to the position, rather than solving the problem using velocities.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Problems, however, arise when multiple constraining forces act on each particle.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] One way to solve this is to loop through every point in a simulation, so that at every point the constraint relaxation of the last is already used to speed up the spread of the information.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] In a simulation this may be implemented by using small time steps for the simulation, using a fixed number of constraint-solving steps per time step, or solving constraints until they are met by a specific deviation.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] When approximating the constraints locally to first order, this is the same as the Gauss–Seidel method.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] For small matrices it is known that LU decomposition is faster.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Large systems can be divided into clusters (for example, each ragdoll = cluster).
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Inside clusters the LU method is used, between clusters the Gauss–Seidel method is used.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The matrix code can be reused: The dependency of the forces on the positions can be approximated locally to first order, and the Verlet integration can be made more implicit.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Sophisticated software, such as SuperLU exists to solve complex problems using sparse matrices.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Specific techniques, such as using (clusters of) matrices, may be used to address the specific problem, such as that of force propagating through a sheet of cloth without forming a sound wave.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Another way to solve holonomic constraints is to use constraint algorithms.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] One way of reacting to collisions is to use a penalty-based system, which basically applies a set force to a point upon contact.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The problem with this is that it is very difficult to choose the force imparted.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Use too strong a force, and objects will become unstable, too weak, and the objects will penetrate each other.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Another way is to use projection collision reactions, which takes the offending point and attempts to move it the shortest distance possible to move it out of the other object.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The Verlet integration would automatically handle the velocity imparted by the collision in the latter case; however, note that this is not guaranteed to do so in a way that is consistent with collision physics (that is, changes in momentum are not guaranteed to be realistic).
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] Instead of implicitly changing the velocity term, one would need to explicitly control the final velocities of the objects colliding (by changing the recorded position from the previous time step).
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] The two simplest methods for deciding on a new velocity are perfectly elastic and inelastic collisions.
[src:fixed-timestep/verlet-integration] A slightly more complicated strategy that offers more control would involve using the coefficient of restitution.
